io.github.prolobjectlink.db

Interface TypedQuery<O>

  • Type Parameters:
    O - Root object template class
    All Superinterfaces:
    Iterator<O>, Serializable
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    Query
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    PrologContainerQuery, PrologTypedQuery

    public interface TypedQuery<O>
extends Iterator<O>, Serializable

    Query is a concept for retrieve objects from object containers. The query object is created through Storage,PersistentContainer which have three variants PersistentContainer.createQuery(Class), PersistentContainer.createQuery(Object) (query by example ) and PersistentContainer.createQuery(Predicate). This methods force to the prolog engine to find all possibles solution for the formulated query and with this solutions the query is builded. All before mentioned methods return a TypedQuery object that hold a solution list that can be retrieved whit the getSolutions() method or simple retrieve the first solution with getSolution(). 

     TypedQuery<Point> query = objectContainer.createQuery(Point.class);
 TypedQuery<Point> query = objectContainer.createQuery(new Point(3, 14));

    TypedQuery object have some useful methods for fix the max solution numbers to retrieve and allow fix the first solution position in the internal list. 

     query.setMaxSolution(2).setFirstSolution(2);
 
 // fix 2 solutions number beginning at second position

    The internal solution list can be ordering in ascendant, descendant or by some given comparator interface implementation. See orderBy(Comparator) 

     List<Point> points = objectContainer.createQuery(Point.class).orderAscending().getSolutions();
 List<Point> points = objectContainer.createQuery(Point.class).orderDescending().getSolutions();

    TypedQuery object allow select the objects to retrieve from all solution internal list given a Predicate implementation of the match method. See TypedQuery#having(Predicate)

    TypedQuery object allow walk over the graph formed by the class relationship described by your fields and retrieve the solutions builded with objects values from visited field. See descend(String) 

     objectContainer.createQuery(Polygon.class).descend("segment0").descend("point0").descend("idp").getSolutions();

    TypedQuery object implement Iterator interface providing an easy way to retrieve each object present in the internal solution list. 

     TypedQuery<Point> query = container.createQuery(Point.class);
 for (Iterator<Point> i = query; e.hasNext();) {
        Point point = (Point) e.next();
        // do something with the retrieved point object
 }
    Since:
    1.0
    Author:
    Jose Zalacain

      • orderAscending

        TypedQuery<O> orderAscending()

        Ascendant ordering of all solutions to be returned by the solutions methods invocation. The order criterion is base in object hash code. Is suggested and very important the Object#hashCode() implementation in the model objects to achieve a corrected solution . The alternation with the TypedQuery#orderDescending() invocation only apply the latest ordering method invocation. For example if we want the list of stored point in ascendant order: 

         List<Point> points = objectContainer.createQuery(Point.class).orderAscending().getSolutions();

        This example return a list with a, b, c, d Point class instances objects

        Returns:
        current instance of TypedQuery with the restriction appended.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        orderDescending(), orderBy(Comparator)

      • orderBy

        TypedQuery<O> orderBy(Comparator<O> comparator)

        Ordering of all solutions to be returned by the solutions methods invocation by a given comparator implementation. This alternative is useful when most specific compare criteria is needed between objects.

        The followed example is equivalent to apply ascending order to point solutions based in point identifier. This example return a list with a, b, c, d Point class instances objects 

         List<Point> points = objectContainer.createQuery(Point.class).orderBy(new Comparator<Point>() {
 
        public int compare(Point o1, Point o2) {
                if (o1.getIdp().compareTo(o2.getIdp()) < 0) {
                        return -1;
                } else if (o1.getIdp().compareTo(o2.getIdp()) > 0) {
                        return 1;
                }
                return 0;
        }
 }).getSolutions();
        Parameters:
        comparator - comparator used for compare an ordering solutions to be returned
        Returns:
        current instance of TypedQuery with the restriction appended.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        orderAscending(), orderDescending()

      • descend

        TypedQuery<Object> descend(String name)

        Create a new TypedQuery descending to object store in the specified field that match with name parameter and present in the objects hold by the query instance. If the specified field is not found in the objects hold by the query instance then an exception is raised. This operation walk the graph represented by object relationship determined by yours field.

        For example suppose a Polygon class is composed by segments objects and one segment by points objects and the point by one point identifier. If we want all identifiers of the initials points of the initials segments from all polygons: 

         objectContainer.createQuery(Polygon.class).descend("segment0").descend("point0").descend("idp").getSolutions();
        Parameters:
        name - class field name to descend
        Returns:
        new instance of TypedQuery with the restriction appended.
        Since:
        1.0
